 the constraint.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 8 Sep 2017 11:55:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-09-11"}
{"id":"1709.02665","submitter":"Pu Gao","authors":"Pu Gao, Reshma Ramadurai, Ian Wanless and Nick Wormald","title":"Full rainbow matchings in graphs and hypergraphs","comments":"This updated version combines another arxiv document:1710.04807","journal-ref":"Combinatorics, Probability and Computing 30, (2021) 762-780","doi":"10.1017/S0963548320000620","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $G$ be a simple graph that is properly edge coloured with $m$ colours and\nlet $\\M=\\{M_1,\\ldots, M_m\\}$ be the set of $m$ matchings induced by the colours\nin $G$. Suppose that $m\\le n-n^{c}$, where $c>9/10$, and every matching in $\\M$\nhas size $n$. Then $G$ contains a full rainbow matching, i.e.\\ a matching that\ncontains exactly one edge from $M_i$ for each $1\\le i\\le m$. This answers an\nopen problem of Pokrovskiy and gives an affirmative answer to a generalisation\nof a special case of a conjecture of Aharoni and Berger.\n  Related results are also found for multigraphs with edges of bounded\nmultiplicity, and for hypergraphs.\n  Finally, we provide counterexamples to several conjectures on full rainbow\nmatchings made by Aharoni and Berger.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 8 Sep 2017 11:59:25 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 22 Jun 2018 05:36:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-17"}
